7 states have no chance. The two closest are Michigan and Pennsylvania. Both need to have significantly higher caseloads than they currently have to get below a 5.0% fatality rate without having any more deaths. It is highly unlikely their caseloads are going to increase significantly (50+%) enough without a corresponding amount of deaths to go below the 5.0% fatality rate.

I believe the total number of fatalities nationally is currently under-counted (at appx. 140,000). However, I believe the current number of infections is also under-counted, and at a higher rate. I am not a denier of Covid-19 and I believe it is serious. In, fact, I do not believe schools should reopen in august for in-person classes. This question is VERY hard to predict because the concept of the spread of the disease and its prevalence is not directly related to the amount of testing. Looking at the chart many of the states that have the highest fatality rate were those hardest-hit earliest. We know deaths lag by 3--5 weeks, at least, after a spike in new cases is observed. However, with the most recent problem areas infections in younger people seem more prevalent, as well as more testing overall, which both lower the measured fatality rate.
I'm trusting the people I admire here, knowing full well C19 has been a weak spot for me.
While positive test rates are increasing, I don't think mortality rates will increase as quickly.

Chances are it will remain around the current level. Split between increasing and decreasing due to so many unknowns (constantly evolving new therapeutic options could spin numbers down vs random clusters in assisted living facilities/high risk age group locales could swing them up). Possible further sowing of distrust and/or creatively curating data to spin for one political party or the other. Many extra variables from other realms.
The fatality rate is a function of total confirmed cases and total deaths. As long as universal testing is unavailable the fatality rate will remain artificially high.

Did calculation using CFR state-wise till date, National CFR for last 14 days, Required number of cases to bring overall CFR below 5% for CFR of 1.356% and then comparing with current number of daily cases. Out of the 10 states above 5% right now: Two states - Indiana and District of Columbia will definitely fall below 5%. So chance of any new state entering above 5% CFR club is slim.

Radical readjustment after not just looking at the source for resolution but at the big picture. What to expect? a) Worst case: death rate increases drastically (!!!!!) among new cases (between bins 2 and 3; much closer to 2 in all scenarios I can imagine) b) Normal case: at least another 1.5M new cases. Fatality rate among them about 1% (current trend). (between bins 1 and 2) c) Best case: more than 1.5M new cases with further decreasing fatality rate (bin 1 only)

July 6 = 12 states at 5% or greater. Assume two new medications for severly ill will actively reduce mortality and that techniques for care provide best practices that can be replicated everywhere. Also assume many new infections are in healther younger patients which will reduce mortality. We'll know in 8 weeks.

I had a first principles story as to why we should expect there to be a nationwide trend towards increasing CFRs. Test positivity ratios are generally increasing, which typically means worsening case ascertainment, and so inflating (observed, crude) CFR above the IFR of (typically) 1%. On this story (and if you assume the epidemic will continue to grow over the next couple of months) you would expect more states to cross 5% than the current 12.

The states that have >5 now are not likely to find enough new cases to drop below 5%. Of the major outbreak states (California, Arizona, Florida, South Carolina, Georgia etc) at least 2 will go above 5% once the lag in deaths has passed.
infection rates are climbing in several states - and while death rate national has decreased to about 5%, it will likely climb, especially in states that are experiencing a spike in cases

current nation-wide death rate is trending toward 5% overall - with infection and hospitalization numbers growing in several key state it is likely that at least half of state will report that rate at the start of September

I'm choosing to depart from the crowd here. Of the current 13 over 5%, I only see a realistic possibility of 2-3 of them dropping under 5%. Example: New York would required something like 500k new cases at a low death rate to get there. This is possible but unlikely. Here are some scenarios: 1) massive new wave starting in August where there are a lot of cases but deaths lag into September 2) far more extensive testing could result in many more asymptomatic cases being detected. However this would require a number like 1M new cases detected to make the numbers work. 3) Most likely: they redefine the case numbers and could people with positive antibody tests and that suddenly drops everyone including NY below 5%.
Today‘s number is 12. Because an increasing number of tests as well as confirmed test the fatality rate is now decreasing.

True mortality rates in any developed country are little more than 1%. This is backed by antibody tests. UK ONS antibody tests estimates 6.3% (possibly > 8%) of population has been infected (4.2 million) with 45,000 fatalities = 1.07%. This should now reduce significantly with new therapies. I agree with @Bobbiekar52 the question is really asking how poor each state's testing is.
